as instead relegated from political centers to village and home, where it continued a vigorous existence for centuries. In analyzing the fate of the Egyptian oracle and of the priesthoods, the function of magical texts, and the dynamics of domestic cults, Frankfurter describes how an ancient culture maintained itself while also being transformed through influences such as Hellenism, Roman government, and Christian dominance. Recognizing the special characteristics of Egypt, which differentiated it from the other Mediterranean cultures that were undergoing simultaneous social and political changes, he departs from the traditional "decline of paganism/triumph of Christianity" model most often used to describe the Roman period. By revealing late Egyptian religion in its Egyptian historical context, he moves us away from scenarios of Christian triumph and shows us how long and how energetically pagan worship survived.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAbydos.  aAmmianus Marcellinus.  aApis bull.  aAtripe.  aBes.  aBlemmyes.  aCanopus (Delta).  aEdfu.  aEunapius.  aGesios.  aHarpocrates.  aHermetica.  aHerodotus.  aHorus.  aJews and Judaism.  aJohn of Lycopolis.  aLibanius of Antioch.  aLucian.  aMandulis.  aManichaeism.  aMin (Pan).  aOsiris.  aPaphnuti.  aPetbe.  aPlutarch.  aRe-Harmachis.  aRufinus.  aSeth (Typhon).  aSyria.  aamulets.  ademons and demonology.  adomestic religion.  aexorcism.  afestivals.  ahagiography.  ahealing and healers.  anaoi.  aoracles.  aterracotta figurines.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691214733zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com